{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17487237","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17487237"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T03:02:33+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T03:02:33+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"289"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"289","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/289"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.37,0.14,0.04,0.06,0.39]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"289"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"89843"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"289","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/289"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"289"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"74034"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"12"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"39"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"309"},{"type":"tags","id":"1094"},{"type":"tags","id":"2436"},{"type":"tags","id":"2899"},{"type":"tags","id":"4974"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"5810"},{"type":"tags","id":"11198"},{"type":"tags","id":"11633"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"30461"},{"type":"contributions","id":"30591"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40002"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42998"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44814"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"89843","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/89843"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 33-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a six-month history of fatigue, joint pain, dysphagia, and muscle weakness. She has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with a pulse rate of 72/min, blood pressure 118/76 mmHg, respiratory rate 14/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. Her hands are examined (Image). Her autoantibody screen shows: ANA positive 1/2500 (speckled pattern), ANCA negative, rheumatoid factor 60 IU/L (\u0026lt;15), and anti-U1-RNP antibody strongly positive.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Scleroderma","Systemic lupus erythematosus","Rheumatoid arthritis","Dermatomyositis","Mixed connective tissue disease"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with a constellation of symptoms and serological findings highly suggestive of a connective tissue disease. The combination of fatigue, joint pain, dysphagia, muscle weakness, Raynaud\u0027s phenomenon, and strongly positive anti-U1-RNP antibody points toward \u003Cstrong\u003Emixed connective tissue disease (MCTD)\u003C/strong\u003E.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMixed connective tissue disease is characterised by overlapping features of several autoimmune conditions including systemic lupus erythematosus, scleroderma, and polymyositis. The hallmark serological finding is high-titer anti-U1-RNP antibody, which is present in this case. Other typical features include Raynaud\u0027s phenomenon (as seen in this patient), arthritis/arthralgia, myositis (explaining the muscle weakness), and oesophageal dysmotility (explaining the dysphagia). The high ANA titer with a speckled pattern is also consistent with MCTD.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EScleroderma\u003C/strong\u003E can present with Raynaud\u0027s phenomenon, puffy fingers that progress to sclerodactyly, and oesophageal dysmotility. However, scleroderma is typically associated with anti-centromere antibodies (in limited cutaneous disease) or anti-Scl-70 antibodies (in diffuse cutaneous disease). While anti-U1-RNP can be positive in scleroderma, it is not the characteristic antibody, and the absence of skin thickening makes pure scleroderma less likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESystemic lupus erythematosus\u003C/strong\u003E can present with fatigue, arthralgia, and positive ANA. However, SLE is typically associated with anti-dsDNA and anti-Sm antibodies rather than isolated high-titer anti-U1-RNP. The presence of dysphagia and muscle weakness without other typical SLE features (such as malar rash, photosensitivity, or renal involvement) makes SLE less likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERheumatoid arthritis\u003C/strong\u003E primarily affects the joints and would not explain the dysphagia and muscle weakness. While rheumatoid factor is positive in this case, it can be positive in various autoimmune conditions including MCTD. The absence of symmetric polyarthritis affecting small joints of hands and feet, and the presence of anti-U1-RNP antibody, make rheumatoid arthritis less likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDermatomyositis\u003C/strong\u003E can present with muscle weakness and dysphagia due to proximal muscle inflammation. However, dermatomyositis typically presents with characteristic skin findings such as Gottron\u0027s papules, heliotrope rash, and V-sign/shawl sign rashes, which are not mentioned in this case. Dermatomyositis is associated with various myositis-specific antibodies rather than anti-U1-RNP.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Mixed connective tissue disease is characterised by overlapping features of systemic lupus erythematosus, scleroderma, and polymyositis.","High-titer anti-U1-RNP antibody is the hallmark serological finding in mixed connective tissue disease.","Clinical features of mixed connective tissue disease include Raynaud\u0027s phenomenon, puffy hands, arthritis, myositis, and oesophageal dysmotility."],"references":["Pepmueller PH. Undifferentiated Connective Tissue Disease, Mixed Connective Tissue Disease, and Overlap Syndromes in Rheumatology.\u00a0Mo Med. 2016;113(2):136\u2013140. Available at: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC6139943/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"74034"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"289"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"18768"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"18768","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/18768"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/951b5cb2-236e-40f5-97c6-69da096b8df6.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/951b5cb2-236e-40f5-97c6-69da096b8df6.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":200,"height":149}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"74034","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/74034"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-11T12:05:52+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-29T20:40:39+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"289"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"89843"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"12","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/12"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc4b","name":"Rheumatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:47+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"t